<article>
    <h1>7&#xD;&#xA;DO SOME COLOUR&#xAD;ING</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201223/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-23"><time>2020-12-23</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE LIVING WELL</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Colour­ing the in­tri­cate de­signs of a pat­tern and mak­ing sure to colour within the lines can help one feel calm yet en­er­gised.</p>
    <p>Dr Annabelle Chow, prin­ci­pal clin­i­cal psy­chol­o­gist at Annabelle Psy­chol­ogy, said mind­ful colour­ing is an ac­tiv­ity that psy­chol­o­gists use to bring aware­ness to the present mo­ment by fo­cus­ing on the colour­ing task at hand and notic­ing shapes, tex­tures and de­signs.</p>
    <p>You can buy adult colour­ing books at book­stores or sim­ply print out blank colour­ing pages with black and white out­lines and colour them as a young child would.</p>
    <p>Dr Chow said: “Through the process of colour­ing, we learn to let go of dis­tract­ing thoughts and re­turn to the fo­cus of the present.”</p>

